### David L. Donoho

David Leigh Donoho, born under the indifferent Californian sky on March 5, 1957, is an American statistician. He is a figure of considerable weight in his field, currently holding the esteemed Anne T. and Robert M. Bass Professorship in the Humanities and Sciences at [Stanford University](/Stanford_University). His intellectual endeavors have charted new territories in the analysis of high-dimensional data, particularly through the development of sophisticated methods for constructing low-dimensional representations. This work, often categorized under [multiscale geometric analysis](/Multiscale_geometric_analysis), delves into the intricate structures hidden within vast datasets. Furthermore, Donoho’s contributions extend to the practical realms of signal processing and data recovery, with his development of [wavelets](/Wavelet) proving instrumental in denoising techniques and the groundbreaking field of [compressed sensing](/Compressed_sensing). His impact on the scientific community was further recognized when he was elected a Member of the prestigious [American Philosophical Society](/American_Philosophical_Society) in 2019, a testament to his profound intellectual contributions that transcend mere technicality.

#### Academic Biography

Donoho’s academic journey began at [Princeton University](/Princeton_University), where he earned his [BA](/Bachelor_of_Arts) in 1978. His undergraduate studies were guided by the formidable [John W. Tukey](/John_W._Tukey), a statistician whose own groundbreaking work in exploratory data analysis and the [Fast Fourier Transform](/Fast_Fourier_Transform) undoubtedly left an indelible mark. Following his undergraduate pursuits, Donoho moved to [Harvard University](/Harvard_University) to undertake doctoral research. It was there, under the tutelage of [Peter J. Huber](/Peter_J._Huber)—a pioneer in robust statistics—that he obtained his [PhD](/PhD) in 1983. Huber's rigorous approach to statistical inference and his emphasis on reliable methods in the face of uncertainty likely shaped Donoho's own analytical framework.

His academic career then saw him join the faculty of the [University of California, Berkeley](/University_of_California,_Berkeley) in 1984, where he spent six years shaping the minds of aspiring statisticians before making the move to [Stanford University](/Stanford_University) in 1990. At Stanford, he has not only continued his own research but has also mentored a significant number of doctoral students. His influence as an advisor is evident in the caliber of researchers who have emerged from his lab, including prominent figures like [Jianqing Fan](/Jianqing_Fan) and [Emmanuel Candès](/Emmanuel_Cand%C3%A8s), both of whom have made substantial contributions to statistics and applied mathematics in their own right. Advising at least twenty doctoral students suggests a deep commitment to fostering the next generation of statistical thinkers, a role he seems to have approached with his characteristic blend of intellectual rigor and perhaps a touch of weary wisdom.

#### Awards and Honors

The recognition of David Donoho’s intellectual prowess is etched in a constellation of prestigious awards and honors. In 1991, he was bestowed the coveted [MacArthur Fellowship](/MacArthur_Fellows_Program), often referred to as a "genius grant," acknowledging his exceptional creativity and promise. The following year, in 1992, he was elected a Fellow of the [American Academy of Arts and Sciences](/American_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences), joining a distinguished company of scholars and leaders.

His contributions were further acknowledged in 1994 when he received the [COPSS Presidents' Award](/COPSS_Presidents%27_Award), an honor bestowed upon young statisticians for significant contributions to the field. In 2001, the [Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics](/Society_for_Industrial_and_Applied_Mathematics) (SIAM) recognized his impact by awarding him the [John von Neumann Prize](/John_von_Neumann_Prize), a testament to his significant contributions to applied mathematics. The year 2002 saw him appointed to the distinguished Bass professorship at Stanford, a position that underscores his academic standing.

By 2009, his influence had reached international recognition. He was elected a Fellow of SIAM, a mark of distinction within the applied mathematics community, and also became a foreign associate of the French [Académie des sciences](/Acad%C3%A9mie_des_sciences), a rare honor for non-French citizens. In the same year, the [University of Chicago](/University_of_Chicago) recognized his academic achievements with an honorary doctorate, a nod to his broader impact on scholarship.

The accolades continued to mount. In 2010, he was jointly awarded the [Norbert Wiener Prize in Applied Mathematics](/Norbert_Wiener_Prize_in_Applied_Mathematics) by SIAM and the [American Mathematical Society](/American_Mathematical_Society), celebrating his work in areas of applied mathematics that have had significant impact. He is also a member of the elite [United States National Academy of Sciences](/United_States_National_Academy_of_Sciences), a body that advises the nation on science and technology. In 2012, he was recognized as a Fellow of the [American Mathematical Society](/American_Mathematical_Society), further cementing his status within the mathematical sciences.

The year 2013 proved particularly significant, as he was awarded the [Shaw Prize](/Shaw_Prize) in Mathematical Sciences, often considered the "Nobel Prize of the East," for his foundational contributions to areas such as [wavelets](/Wavelet) and [compressed sensing](/Compressed_sensing). In 2016, the [University of Waterloo](/University_of_Waterloo) honored him with an honorary degree, acknowledging his global academic influence. Culminating this impressive list, in 2018, he received the Gauss Prize from the International Mathematical Union, one of the highest honors in mathematics, for his outstanding contributions to scientific computing and applied mathematics.

